AGI -&nbsp;In a climate of tension and uncertainty, the &nbsp;Ciad&nbsp; elects its president today.» A crucial event for France and the West in general, of which N'Djamena represents the last pawn in the Sahel region now under the influence of military regimes and Russia. There are ten candidates, including the transition president, General Mahamat Idriss Dèby, and his prime minister, Succès Masra.> A comparison to the centre of the attention of the international community, but with a problem not recently: many Chadians are not registered in the electoral lists. After three decades of government of President Idriss Dèby Itno - always supported by Paris - killed in combat in 2021, his son brought by a group of generals replaced him as head of the country. Monday' the president of transition, candidate of the Patriotic Movement of Salvation (Mps) - founded by the deceased father - will try to legitimize the acquired power inconstitutional way, but the outcome of the urns is uncertain >, in a regional climate of anti-French winds and anti-colonialist >, to assert instead its national sovereignty. In this context the transparency of the presidential elections has already been questioned by its main rival and prime minister, Succès Masra, who believes that "the place of the French army is in France". A rhetoric that has been the same as that carried out for a few years by opponents and military coup authors in the nearby Mali, Niger and Burkina Faso. Most of the time since the soldiers of Paris were subsequently hunted by Bamako, Ouagadougou and Niamey, France intends to maintain its military presence firmly in&nbsp; Chad, although at the same time it proclaims the desire to go beyond its exclusive security cooperation. "We must remain, and of course we will," said Jean-Marie Bockel, "personal envoy" of President Emmanuel Macron, last March 7 after a meeting with the transition president Mahamat Idriss Dèby. An eventual break between Paris and N'Djamena is difficult to predict, largely because the Franco-Indian military relations have a long history of co-dependence.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The African country and its " desert warriors" occupy a special place in the imagination of the French army, present in this territory almost uninterruptedly for over a century.> First colony to join Free France on August 26, 1940, the &nbsp; Chad&nbsp; remained partly administered by the French army until 1965, five years after the independence of the country. Since then, the "desert carrier" - as it was nicknamed for its strategic position that allowed Paris to project its troops into the region - holds the record of the largest number of French external operations. From Operation Limousin (1969-1971), to protect President Francois Tombalbaye from the rebel factions of Sudan, to Operation Sparviero (1986-2014) against the invasion of the Libyan troops of Muammar Gheddafi, the French army subsequently brought to power Hisse'ne Habre' in 1982, sentenced in 2016 to life for the crimes against humanity, committed during 1990. He then accompanied Habre's overthrow by Idriss Dèby eight years later and bombed the rebel columns that threatened De'by's power in 2019. For his part, the&nbsp;Ciad&nbsp; sent his troops to the forefront when France was involved in the Sahel against jihadists in 2013. A thousand French soldiers are still stationed at the N'Djamena Airbase, from which Mirage fighters take off every day, providing valuable information on rebel movements at the borders. But the justification for the maintenance of the operational center of the French forces in the Sahel in N'Djamena, which has subdued to "Barkhane", is questionable, especially because the Chadian capital is several thousand kilometers away from the theater of operations against the jihadist groups in the center of the Sahel, which became inaccessible to the French soldiers. The &nbsp;Ciad&nbsp; is no longer a projection base, but remains a central issue in a region shocked by crisis, coups and the growing influence of Russia, > which is unfolding its paramilitaries in four neighboring countries: Libya, Sudan, Central African Republic and Niger. Just yesterday in Niamey, the capital of the Niger, the Russian soldiers were deployed in the airbase 101, which also houses American troops, after the military junta in power decided to end a military cooperation agreement with Washington and expel US forces.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"N'Djamena knows how to exploit its position as a besieged citadel. The members of the Chadian security apparatus do not hesitate to evoke the spectrum of Russia to frighten the West and induce it to make concessions, with great disappointment of civil society and opposition, while diversifying its security partnerships in the direction of the United Arab Emirates, Turkey, Hungary", analyzes the French daily Le Monde. In this climate, the resentment of many Chadians thirsting for change is growing and for which France now seems to be only an obstacle.
&nbsp;
At N'Djamena no one has forgotten President Macron's speech, the only Western Head of State to attend the funeral of Idriss Dèby> on 23 April 2021. "France will never allow the stability and integrity of the &nbsp; Chad&nbsp; they are questioned", then declared the holder of the Elysée, while the rebel troops advanced to the Chadian capital. This episode has been interpreted by many citizens as the Paris approval of a dynastic succession to power. Three years later, and despite the promises made, nothing seems to have changed when Bockel proclaimed his "admiration" for the transition, only a week after the main opposition leader, Yaya Dillo, had been killed - at the end of February - by the army in an assault at the headquarters of his party, less than three months after the presidential elections. Since then, the gap between a shifting youth and the former colony is inexorably widening. Whether it is true or false, it remains deeply rooted in people's minds the opinion that the winner will be the one chosen by Paris and that, in giving support to power, France shares the responsibility for the mismanagement of the &nbsp; Chad. At the same time, according to several analysts, it is possible that the Ciadian authorities are mobilizing the public hostile to the French military presence > to try to gain points in view of the presidential elections. As to avoid being called into question in an increasingly tense political sequence, on April 25, the United States announced the temporary withdrawal of some of their troops in&nbsp; Chad, following a disagreement with the Greater State of the Air Force. France, which repeatedly proclaims its will to reduce its military presence in Africa and to reinvent the relationship with its former colonies, in&nbsp; Chad&nbsp; seems to do the exact opposite.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

