AGI -&nbsp;Today the Eurotunnel, which connects France and England under the Channel, is 30 years old and looks at new challenges, before all to exploit its unused potential after the crisis of Brexit and pandemic, which significantly reduced its activity. On 6 May 1994, French President Francois Mitterrand and Queen Elizabeth of England opened this 50-kilometre railway tunnel, of which 37 submarines under the Channel, at a depth of 60 meters below sea level. This great engineering firm, which is still the world's longest underwater tunnel, soon became a financial fiasco for the dealership company, when it became clear that the traffic expectations with which it was built were exorbitant. In 1986, British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher accepted the Canterbury Treaty with France for its construction, provided that the risk was sustained by private investors and that it did not cost a cent to the British taxpayer. After the shareholders cleared the initial losses of millions of dollars, the Eurotunnel managed to constantly gain market shares compared to ferries in the transport of vehicles and aircraft in the transport of passengers on the Paris-London and Brussels-Brussels routes. Currently, about 400 trains pass through the double tunnel in both directions, with a third service channel for maintenance work and emergency evacuation, but its potential capacity with the current infrastructure is 1,000 trains and could be expanded with new investments. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Last year 2,25 million cars passed (+6% compared to 2022, with a market share of 58%) and 1,2 million trucks (-17%, with a market share of 36%). The goods transported by these trucks, and those on trains dedicated to the transport of various materials and products, account for approximately 25% of the value of trade between the EU and the United Kingdom. The Eurotunnel must face the competition, that the company of Getlink dealerships clearly considers unfair, of the three ferry companies that operate on the Channel, which, in order to lower the tariffs to the carriers, have assumed their employees according to the regime of international marine law, well below the European social minimums. As for passengers, with 10 million passengers transported to Eurostar TGV last year, when Getlink estimates that its infrastructure is now ready for double, the aim of the dealership is to open new lines and that other operators turn forward and compete. New destinations from London include Cologne and Frankfurt in Germany, Geneva and Zurich in Switzerland or Marseille and Bordeaux in France. The objective is to double the number of passenger lines using Eurotunnel in ten years. Two companies have already expressed their interest in managing their trains through Eurotunnel: Evolyn - owned by the Spanish family Cosmen, a shareholder of Mobico - who would like to manage the route Paris-London from 2025; and the Dutch group Heurtrain, which plans to put trains on the corridors London-Paris-Bruxelles-Amsterdam by 2028.&nbsp;

